	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Xious: I use Proteus by Labcenter.  The base version I bought cost me $250 and is limited to 500 device pins (not counting vias), but that's been enough so far.  It does include an autorouter, but I wouldn't hope to get anything really great out of any autorouter (I guess there are better/more expensive ones, I've never seen a free one).  I use the autorouter just to see if my parts placement is good or not.  99% of the time I undo the results.  Since it won't touch manual tracks, you can nudge it in the right direction, or just use it to get some ideas.  That's method I used to make <a href="http://www.parodius.com/~memblers/nes/squeedo/pics/yellow.jpg" class="postlink">this board</a>, which is probably overkill with it's density and pervasive grounding.
<br />
<br />Lets try to keep most of this in one thread.  Since you made the first post I think you can edit it to change the subject title, if you want to later.
<br />
<br />tepples: Yeah, for sound processing you will definitely get much more "bang for your buck" by using an MCU.  Especially if you want memory for samples.  The synth code I've been writing and building on PC <a href="http://membler-industries.com/squeedo/Squeedo%202010-08-30%20-%20TMNT4%20by%20Konami.mp3" class="postlink">(example)</a> is designed to be portable to the PIC32.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


